docs.abstract: Ambitious moves to shift power to workers are being embraced by several Democratic presidential contenders.
docs.snippet: Ambitious moves to shift power to workers are being embraced by several Democratic presidential contenders.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Bernie Sanders ran for president in 2016, his campaign was strikingly pro-labor. He proposed a $15-an-hour minimum wage, which was much further than most mainstream Democrats, including Hillary Clinton, were willing to go. He denounced a trans-Pacific trade deal that was anathema to many unions. He endorsed an organizing method, known as card check, that would allow workers to unionize without holding a secret-ballot election.

headline.main: Candidates Grow Bolder on Labor, and Not Just Bernie Sanders
headline.print_headline: Democrats Grow Bolder With Pro-Labor Policies
